‘ Pontio is writing the tale of the civil wars, a difficult and delicate task. We can afford to let even his tragedies wait awhile, till the great and brave orator of the forum and the, senate, and the conqueror of Illyria, has given us his history. In our eagerness we seem already to hear the trumpets and see the flashing amour, to hear him reading to us of the fall of chieftains and the conquest of all the world save Cato’s stubborn soul. Ay, Jugurtha is avenged now! What land or sea is not red with the blood of our sratricidal wax-s? But stay, my Muse, these are no
